### Refs

Refs provide a way to access DOM nodes or React elements directly. Use them for imperative operations like focusing inputs, measuring elements, or integrating with third-party libraries.

---

### Creating Refs with useRef

```jsx
import { useRef } from 'react';

function TextInput() {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  const focusInput = () => {
    inputRef.current.focus();
  };

  return (
    <>
      <input ref={inputRef} type="text" />
      <button onClick={focusInput}>Focus Input</button>
    </>
  );
}
```

### When to Use Refs

| Use Case | Example |
|----------|---------|
| Managing focus | `inputRef.current.focus()` |
| Text selection | `inputRef.current.select()` |
| Media playback | `videoRef.current.play()` |
| Animations | Triggering imperative animations |
| Third-party DOM libraries | Integrating D3, Chart.js |

### Refs and State

Refs do not cause re-renders when changed. Use state for values that affect the UI and refs for values that don't:

```jsx
const countRef = useRef(0);
// Changing countRef.current does NOT re-render
```

> **Key Point:** Avoid overusing refs. They are an escape hatch for imperative code. Default to state and props for declarative React patterns.

codeExample:
import { useRef } from 'react';

function VideoPlayer() {
  const videoRef = useRef(null);

  const play = () => videoRef.current.play();
  const pause = () => videoRef.current.pause();

  return (
    <div>
      <video ref={videoRef} src="video.mp4" />
      <button onClick={play}>Play</button>
      <button onClick={pause}>Pause</button>
    </div>
  );
}
